40|$|In this paper, {{we study}} the {{behavior}} of indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> using daily data for five years from seven production departments of a manufacturing firm. We address two questions: (1) Are indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> proportional to <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs,</b> the cost driver employed in the existing cost accounting system to allocate indirect costs? and (2) Are indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> associated with batch-related and product-sustaining cost drivers {{in addition to the}} unit-related driver, <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs?</b> Our empirical results reject the proportionality hypothesis for all seven departments. Our results also reveal that while <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> are significantly associated with indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> in all seven departments, number of setups is also significantly associated with indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> in all seven departments, and number of distinct parts is significantly associated in six. Interestingly, we find that despite multiple factors driving indirect production <b>labor</b> <b>costs,</b> the simple method of estimating these costs as a proportion of only <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> performs remarkably well in predicting daily costs. 3 A Time-Series Analysis of Indirect Production <b>Labor</b> <b>Costs</b> 1...|$|R
50|$|Variance {{analysis}} is {{usually associated with}} explaining the difference (or variance) between actual costs and the standard costs allowed for the good output. For example, the difference in materials costs {{can be divided into}} a materials price variance and a materials usage variance. The difference between the actual <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> and the standard <b>direct</b> <b>labor</b> <b>costs</b> can be divided into a rate variance and an efficiency variance. The difference in manufacturing overhead can be divided into spending, efficiency, and volume variances. Mix and yield variances can also be calculated.|$|R
